thread.title_full: Local Links: Irving's Austin Connelly advances in Web.com Tour Q-school | Dallas Morning News

author: Bill Nichols
title: Local Links: Irving's Austin Connelly advances in Web.com Tour Q-school
text:
Irving's Austin Connelly, who made the cut at the AT&T Byron Nelson as an amateur, and three-time TCU All-American Julien Brun were among the 23 players who advanced to the second stage of Web.com Tour Q-school at Lantana Golf Club on Friday. Austin Connelly, 18, tied for the final spot at 9-under 279, decided in August to turn pro insidead of playing at Arkansas.
Alex Moon of Dallas, a former Texas player, shot 19-under 269 to finish second, six shots behind Jim Knous of Englewood, Calif.
The final stage is Dec. 10-13 at PGA National in Palm Beach Gardens, Fla.
Senior leads TCU to tournament title
Senior Paul Barjon won the individual title, and TCU won the Connecticut Cup at Ellington Ridge Golf Course. It was the Frogs' final event of the fall season.
TCU finished 19-under 845, marking the first time in the event's seven years that a team finished under par. Boston College and Dartmouth tied for second at 862. This was TCU's first team title since the Wyoming Desert Intercollegiate last spring and 32nd team title for coach Bill Montigel.
Barjon shot a final-round 68 to finish at 11-under 205, one stroke clear of junior teammate Chelso Barrett.
Dallas junior wins North Texas Classic
Dallas' Mark Reppe fired a final-round 4-under 68 to claim the Legend Junior Tour's inaugural North Texas Classic by one stroke over four players at Tangle Ridge Golf Club in Grand Prairie.
Reppe finished five under in boys 15-18, followed by Kyle Robinson of Fayetteville, Ark., Plano's Parker Coody, Richardson's Tommy Boone and Arlington's Caleb Hicks.
Dawson Ovard of Frisco shot 68-73 to win boys 14-under by one stroke over Evan Vo of Austin. Jennie Park of Carrollton (71-71) captured girls 12-18 by two shots over Dallas' Macy Holliday.
394-yard shot wins long drive title
Tim Burke of Orlando, Fla., won the World Long Drive Championship for the second time in three years, beating Jeremy Easterly in the final with a 394-yard drive in Thackerville, Okla. Easterly had a 386-yard drive in the final.
